Class Output<T extends TType>

java.lang.Object
org.tensorflow.Output<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
org.tensorflow.ndarray.Shaped, Op, Operand<T>
public final class Output<T extends TType> extends Object implements Operand<T>
A symbolic handle to a tensor produced by an Operation.

An Output<T> is a symbolic handle to a Tensor<T>. The value of the tensor is computed by executing the Operation in a Session.

By implementing the Operand interface, instances of this class also act as operands to Op instances.

    • asTensor

      public T asTensor()
      Returns the tensor at this output.

      This operation is only supported on the outputs of an operation executed eagerly. For graph environments, output tensors must be fetched by running a session, using Session.Runner.fetch(Output).

      It is recommended to close explicitly the returned tensor as soon as possible, since the garbage collector is not aware of the amount of memory it consumes, which can be significant.

      Specified by:
      asTensor in interface Operand<T extends TType>
      Returns:
      tensor
      Throws:
      IllegalStateException - if this output results from a graph
      ClassCastException - if the type of the tensor and this output are unexpectedly incompatible
      See Also:
      • EagerSession

    • op

      public Operation op()
      Description copied from interface: Op
      Return this unit of computation as a single Operation.

      For a raw op, the returned value correspond to the TensorFlow operation wrapped by this op.

      For a composite op, the returned value usually correspond to the last operation invoked in a chain or to a NoOp grouping one or more operations as a single unit of computation.

      Specified by:
      op in interface Op
      Returns:

    • asOutput

      public Output<T> asOutput()
      Description copied from interface: Operand
      Returns the symbolic handle of the tensor.

      Inputs to TensorFlow operations are outputs of another TensorFlow operation. This method is used to obtain a symbolic handle that represents the computation of the input.
